== StumpWM ==
Spend some time with GNU Emacs and the user is invited to learn EmacsLisp. I enjoyed EmacsLisp so much I started looking into other lisps, finding CommonLisp and StumpWM.

I've been using StumpWM for a few years and find it to be the best window manager for my purposes - which is really just an instance of GNU Emacs and an instance of Chromium.

== Configuration ==
I will get around to cleaning up my dot emacs file and putting it online eventually.

My configuration is split into the following hierarchy:
* ~/.emacs.d/init.el
* ~/.emacs.d/config-el/general-config.el
* ~/.emacs.d/config-el/writing-config.el
* ~/.emacs.d/config-el/programming-config.el
* ~/.emacs.d/config-el/user-config.el
* ~/.emacs.d/config-el/key-bindings-config.el
* ~/.emacs.d/config-el/appearance-config.el

This configuration sets a number of variables in *init.el* before loading the files in the *config-el* directory; it is structured such that everything included in *general-config.el* is available by default with GNU Emacs 24, while everything included in *user-config.el* are packages (and settings) which I have found useful using [[ELPA]]. I believe the function of the remaining configurations should be evident from their names. These configurations tend to /include/ packages from [[ELPA]]; even though there is the *general-config.el* and *user-config.el* distinction. The *general-config.el* file sets a number of packages to be downloaded which the configuration "requires", although the corresponding command needs to be manually called.

I guess this is an attempt at writing a "general" configuration file another user could easily adapt to their own purposes; at some point I was interested in writing a document to the effect of "GNU Emacs for Writers".

